<DOC><DOCNO> AP881005-0266 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-10-05-88 0059EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r f PM-BusinessHighlights 1stAdd   10-05 0485</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Business Highlights, 1st Add,0510</SECOND><DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   NBC's coverage of the Summer Olympics dominatedtwo weeks of prime time but concluded Sunday with an average ratingbelow the guarantee NBC gave advertisers, and that will cost thenetwork millions.   NBC, which paid more than $300 million for the rights to theOlympics, will not comment on the loss.   The Wall Street Journal reported Tuesday the network will haveto give as much as $70 million in commercial time to advertiserswho didn't get as high a rating as they were promised.</TEXT><DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Britain's government has ordered the KuwaitInvestment Office to slash its 21.68 percent stake in BritishPetroleum Co. PLC by more than half.   The government said Tuesday the holding could conflict with thepublic interest and gave the Kuwaiti concern a year to reduce itsstake to no more than 9.9 percent.   The reduction is likely to result in a huge loss for theLondon-based investment arm of the Kuwaiti government, which saidit was ``extremely dissatisfied'' with the decision.</TEXT><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The people who engineered a seven-year boycottagainst Nestle SA to fight the promotion of infant formula in ThirdWorld nations want to resume the battle.   Douglas A. Johnson, chairman of Action for CorporateAccountability, called Tuesday for a renewal of the boycott,arguing Nestle has failed to live up to the agreements it signed in1984 that ended the original action.   This time, said Johnson, the group is expanding the boycott toAmerican Home Products Corp., which it said is the second largestdistributor of infant formula in developing nations.</TEXT><DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Bank of New York Co. has won another legalbattle in its yearlong $1.2 billion bid to acquire Irving Bank Corp.   An appeals court Tuesday struck down a key provision of Irving's``poison pill'' anti-takeover defense.   But Irving said it would ask the state's highest court, theCourt of Appeals, to review the ruling from the New York StateSupreme Court's appellate division.</TEXT><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The House Banking Committee has voted in favorof abolishing the much-criticized federal agency created to manageand dispose of the assets of insolvent savings institutions.   The Federal Asset Disposition Association was formed by theFederal Home Loan Bank Board in 1985 to assist the Federal Savingsand Loan Insurance Corp. in the management of acquired assets.   FADA has been accused by members of Congress of favoritism,conflicts of interest and mismanagement of the $3.9 billion inloans and real estate in its care. The committee voted Tuesday.</TEXT><BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE><TEXT>   The stock market declined for the third consecutive sessionTuesday. The Dow Jones average of 30 industrial stocks fell 3.20points to 2,102.06.   The dollar and gold finished mixed.   Bond prices were unchanged to slightly lower.   Crude oil futures prices steadied, while grain and soybeanfutures rallied.</TEXT></DOC>